\details{
\strong{Which hypotheses are included:} All named hypotheses contribute to the
LCA — \code{"specific_candidate"}, \code{"unreferenced_species"} (congener without reference
sequence), \code{"unreferenced_genus"} (family-level unreferenced taxon: named species
from a genus absent in the reference), and \code{"unresolved_species"} (a species from a
census-complete genus whose identity is ambiguous among the known reference members;
produced by \code{\link[TaxaLikely:apply_coverage_constraints]{TaxaLikely::apply_coverage_constraints()}} with
\code{constraint_behavior = "relabel"}). Only the \code{"unknown_species"} catch-all row is
excluded.

\strong{LCA resolution:} The LCA is determined by walking taxonomy ranks from
finest to coarsest and finding the finest rank at which all plausible
hypotheses agree. Explicit taxonomy columns (e.g. \code{family}, \code{genus},
\code{species}) are used when present in \code{posterior_df}; genus can always be
derived from a species binomial even when no \code{genus} column is present.
Family and above require an explicit column.

\strong{Taxonomy columns in posterior_df:} \code{assign_taxa_llm()} automatically
carries taxonomy columns from \code{match_df} into its output. When using the
full pipeline (\code{compute_posterior()}), taxonomy columns pass through from
\code{evaluate_likelihoods()}. Unreferenced species rows have \code{NA} in taxonomy columns;
set \code{lookup_missing_taxonomy = TRUE} to attempt lookup via
\code{TaxaTools::verify_taxon_names()}.

\strong{Threshold interaction:}
\code{min_posterior} and \code{cumulative_threshold} work together:
\code{min_posterior} removes obvious noise hypotheses first (those with
negligible posterior mass), then \code{cumulative_threshold} selects the
plausible set from the remainder. Setting \code{min_posterior = 0} disables
noise filtering; setting it too high (e.g. 0.3) may exclude genuine
competing hypotheses. \code{cumulative_threshold = 0.9} is analogous to a
90\\% credible interval; increase toward 0.95--0.99 for more conservative
assignments (more upranking to genus/family); decrease to 0.8 for more
aggressive species-level calls.

\strong{LCA method:}
Lowest Common Ancestor is the standard conservative consensus method in
molecular systematics (Huson et al., 2007, MEGAN). The implementation
walks from finest to coarsest rank and stops at the first rank where all
plausible hypotheses agree.
